      <article class="post-1314 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-featured-work tag-atomistic-modeling tag-carbon-nanotubes tag-chiral-angle-selectivity" id="post-1314">
       <header class="entry-header">
        <h1 class="entry-title">
         <a href="http://biygroup.blogs.rice.edu/archives/1314" rel="bookmark" title="Permalink to Two-faced edge makes nanotubes obey">
          Two-faced edge makes nanotubes obey
         </a>
        </h1>
        <div class="entry-meta">
         <span class="sep">
          Posted on
         </span>
         <a href="http://biygroup.blogs.rice.edu/archives/1314" rel="bookmark" title="10:37 am">
          <time class="entry-date" datetime="2018-07-26T10:37:04+00:00" pubdate="">
           July 26, 2018
          </time>
         </a>
         <span class="by-author">
          <span class="sep">
           by
          </span>
          <span class="author vcard">
           <a class="url fn n" href="http://biygroup.blogs.rice.edu/archives/author/esp1" rel="author" title="View all posts by e.penev">
            e.penev
           </a>
          </span>
         </span>
        </div>
        <!-- .entry-meta -->
       </header>
       <!-- .entry-header -->
       <div class="entry-content">
        <div addthis:title="Two-faced edge makes nanotubes obey " addthis:url="http://biygroup.blogs.rice.edu/archives/1314" class="addthis_toolbox addthis_default_style ">
         <a class="addthis_button_facebook_like" fb:like:layout="button_count">
         </a>
         <a class="addthis_button_tweet">
         </a>
         <a class="addthis_button_google_plusone" g:plusone:size="medium">
         </a>
         <a class="addthis_counter addthis_pill_style">
         </a>
        </div>
        <div class="pf-content">
         <h2>
          <em>
           Rice theorists find mechanism behind nearly pure nanotubes from the unusual catalyst
           <img alt="" class="alignright wp-image-1315" height="300" sizes="(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px" src="http://biygroup.blogs.rice.edu/files/2018/07/cnts_on_CoW-28essld.jpg" srcset="http://biygroup.blogs.rice.edu/files/2018/07/cnts_on_CoW-28essld.jpg 600w, http://biygroup.blogs.rice.edu/files/2018/07/cnts_on_CoW-28essld-300x300.jpg 300w" width="300"/>
          </em>
         </h2>
         <p>
          Growing a batch of
          <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carbon_nanotube">
           carbon nanotubes
          </a>
          that are all the same may not be as simple as researchers had hoped, according to Rice University scientists.
         </p>
         <p>
          Rice materials theorist
          <a href="https://biygroup.blogs.rice.edu/">
           Boris Yakobson
          </a>
          and his team bucked a theory that when growing nanotubes in a furnace, a catalyst with a specific atomic arrangement and symmetry would reliably make carbon nanotubes of like
          <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chirality">
           chirality
          </a>
          , the angle of its carbon-atom lattice.
         </p>
         <p>
          Instead, they found the catalyst in question starts nanotubes with a variety of chiral angles but redirects almost all of them toward a fast-growing variant known as (12,6). The cause appears to be a
          <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Janus">
           Janus-like
          </a>
          interface that is composed of
          <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Graphene_nanoribbon#mediaviewer/File:Cnt_gnrarm_v3.gif">
           armchair
          </a>
          and
          <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Graphene_nanoribbon#mediaviewer/File:Cnt_zz_v3.gif">
           zigzag
          </a>
          segments – and ultimately changes how nanotubes grow.
         </p>
         <p>
          The Rice theoretical study detailed in the American Chemical Society journal
          <em>
           <a href="https://pubs.acs.org/doi/10.1021/acs.nanolett.8b02283">
            Nano Letters
           </a>
          </em>
          could be a step toward catalysts that produce homogeneous batches of nanotubes, Yakobson said.
         </p>
         <p>
          – See more at
          <a href="http://news.rice.edu/2018/07/26/two-faced-edge-makes-nanotubes-obey-2/">
           Rice News
          </a>
         </p>
        </div>
       </div>
