      <!-- #post-1291 -->
      <article class="post-1275 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-group-news" id="post-1275">
       <header class="entry-header">
        <h1 class="entry-title">
         <a href="http://biygroup.blogs.rice.edu/archives/1275" rel="bookmark" title="Permalink to Graphene grows stronger against the wind">
          Graphene grows stronger against the wind
         </a>
        </h1>
        <div class="entry-meta">
         <span class="sep">
          Posted on
         </span>
         <a href="http://biygroup.blogs.rice.edu/archives/1275" rel="bookmark" title="12:30 pm">
          <time class="entry-date" datetime="2018-03-12T12:30:23+00:00" pubdate="">
           March 12, 2018
          </time>
         </a>
         <span class="by-author">
          <span class="sep">
           by
          </span>
          <span class="author vcard">
           <a class="url fn n" href="http://biygroup.blogs.rice.edu/archives/author/esp1" rel="author" title="View all posts by e.penev">
            e.penev
           </a>
          </span>
         </span>
        </div>
        <!-- .entry-meta -->
       </header>
       <!-- .entry-header -->
       <div class="entry-content">
        <div addthis:title="Graphene grows stronger against the wind " addthis:url="http://biygroup.blogs.rice.edu/archives/1275" class="addthis_toolbox addthis_default_style ">
         <a class="addthis_button_facebook_like" fb:like:layout="button_count">
         </a>
         <a class="addthis_button_tweet">
         </a>
         <a class="addthis_button_google_plusone" g:plusone:size="medium">
         </a>
         <a class="addthis_counter addthis_pill_style">
         </a>
        </div>
        <div class="pf-content">
         <h2>
          Rice, Oak Ridge National Laboratory technique grows pristine foot-long graphene
         </h2>
         <div class="wp-caption alignright" id="attachment_1276" style="width: 300px">
          <img alt="" class="wp-image-1276" height="202" sizes="(max-width: 290px) 100vw, 290px" src="http://biygroup.blogs.rice.edu/files/2018/03/nmat_gr-1u7zwsm-632x441.jpg" srcset="http://biygroup.blogs.rice.edu/files/2018/03/nmat_gr-1u7zwsm-632x441.jpg 632w, http://biygroup.blogs.rice.edu/files/2018/03/nmat_gr-1u7zwsm-768x536.jpg 768w, http://biygroup.blogs.rice.edu/files/2018/03/nmat_gr-1u7zwsm-430x300.jpg 430w, http://biygroup.blogs.rice.edu/files/2018/03/nmat_gr-1u7zwsm.jpg 800w" width="290"/>
          <p class="wp-caption-text">
           Original image by Andy Sproles/Oak Ridge National Laboratory, U.S. Dept. of Energy.
          </p>
         </div>
         <p>
          Is there a way to make big sheets of pristine graphene or other two-dimensional materials? The answer is blowing in the wind.
         </p>
         <p>
          That’s the heart of a discovery by scientists at Rice University, New Mexico State University and the Department of Energy’s Oak Ridge National Laboratory (ORNL) who grew single-atom-thick graphene monocrystals to unprecedented sizes.
         </p>
         <p>
          The technique developed by ONRL researcher and lead author Ivan Vlassiouk, New Mexico scientist
          <a href="https://web.nmsu.edu/~snsm/group/">
           Sergei Smirnov
          </a>
          and Rice materials theorist and co-author
          <a href="http://biygroup.blogs.rice.edu/">
           Boris Yakobson
          </a>
          in principle produces pristine graphene of unlimited size and makes it suitable for roll-to-roll production. Their process deposits a narrow band of hydrocarbon precursor onto a moving substrate, with a buffer gas blowing the carbon atoms toward the growing front. Once the atoms grab ahold of the substrate and crystallize into a seed of graphene, the buffer wind prompts them to cohere into a single growing sheet.
         </p>
         <p>
          The researchers reported in
          <a href="http://doi.org/10.1038/s41563-018-0019-3">
           Nature Materials
          </a>
          their success in growing atom-thin sheets of graphene a foot long and a few inches wide, limited only by the width of the equipment. The single crystal of two-dimensional carbon grows at an inch per hour in a custom-built chemical vapor deposition (CVD) furnace.
         </p>
         <p>
          The work is featured also on the popular YouTube Science channel
          <em>
           SciShow
          </em>
          :
         </p>
         <p>
          <iframe allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen" frameborder="0" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/7NHTkudyaRE?rel=0&amp;start=177;end=332" width="560">
          </iframe>
         </p>
         <p>
          – See more at
          <a href="http://news.rice.edu/2018/03/12/graphene-grows-stronger-against-the-wind-2/">
           Rice News
          </a>
         </p>
        </div>
       </div>
